text: I heard about this movie and I just had to read the book first. I'm confused as to why people are complaining about Amandla as Starr, in the book, Starr is described as 'caramel-skinned' (but she hates being called that) and her mum is 'high yella' while her dad is dark-skinned. Also, did I mention that the mother's brother's name is Carlos? Sure, a non-hispanic person may have a Hispanic name, but that and the 'high yella' painted to me a picture of some sort of admixture, so Amandla does fit the profile, by skin colour and by admixture. The dark-skinned girl on the cover is what threw people off, and I thought Starr was dark-skinned too from the cover but she's really not. Apparently, the cover has nothing to do with Starr's physicality but with #BLM. Yes, colorism is absolutely a thing and we have to work towards fixing that but in this case, it appears that the casting of Starr was done by the book. Turns out, even the writer recommended that Amandla be Starr.

text: This is gonna be the first time I've read a book way before there was mention of a film, and now I understand the partial frustrations that may arise when your favorite book is being adapted into a film üôÉ  In the book, Khalil doesn't pick up his hairbrush while instructed to stand beside the car. He only peeps in through the window to ask if Starr is okay. By making him take out a *hairbrush* , despite being pulled over and instructed to stand beside the car, the movie makes him look more careless/disobedient than he was--making it easier to defend the cop in this situation.  But to clarify/discuss a little about what happened in the book, while Khalil did initially respond with annoyance toward the cop, we *know* he didn't do anything wrong to begin with. Granted Khalil could have sounded more respectful/polite as he asked why he was pulled over, but he is human. And when one's pulled over for presumably no reason, besides perhaps racial profiling, we can see why one would be a bit annoyed. The cop's human too, so of course this rubs him the wrong way. But, going off how the event played out in the book, to make the assumption Khalil was reaching for a gun because he ducked his head in a window while the cop was at his car? Khalil should have known better than to move (even if his intention was just to check on his friend), but come on. That was the reason to shoot? *Several* times? The cop's retelling of the events with false information even suggests that the cop realizes how bad the telling of the true events would make him look. So in this specific instance, one should most certainly side with the victims.   Anyways, back to the original point of this comment, the use of the hairbrush in that movie scene is bothersome for me as one who read the book, but I have to remind myself that this is an adaptation of the book--not a carbon copy. I'm still excited to see how well they did depicting the story along with its overall message! ü§ôüèæ

text: No hate to Amandla (or Zendaya she's my idol), I'm super hype to see this movie, but It's always Zendaya or Amandla that's cast as black women in movies. As a dark skin teen who was super psyched for a dark skin or medium skin girl to play the role, I was a little disappointed, but not surprised, by their choice for the lead role. Amandla's gonna be amazing though, no hate towards her at all, I'm still super psyched to see it. I just wish they would venture out and discover all the amazing dark skinned actresses that could do this role just as well and fit the description in the book. It's more than just skin tone, it shows the implicit effect of colorism in society and the movie industry.

text: "I got a boyfriend." "Yeah, I heard. It's all good." "Really?" "Been together all our lives, Starr. *We got time.* " When you think about this scene after what happens, it makes you want to cry even harder. Innocent lives are lost...Their dreams and hopes taken away due to irrational fear and hate.   It saddens me how realistic this scenario is. And yet nothing changes. Same events repeat, just a different name. We're becoming used to news like this...and that's when you know that humanity has come to the lowest point possible. When will things like these become a part of history textbooks that children read and find incomprehensible that it even happened? I don't want this to be our present.

text: and please realise that the brush Khalil is holding/using is not the point. it may look funny (or as I've also read in other comments, 'stupid' or 'foolish') to some people, as he seems to be goofing around or trying to lighten the mood, but the message is that sometimes the trigger gets pulled a second too soon for things as 'funny' as a hair brush. in situations as tense as 2 black people being pulled over *without a clear reason*, even a *hair brush* can be seen as gun or something else (I'm not judging the act of Khalil taking the hair brush, I simply want to make it clear that it's not intended as a joke. remember how a great number of real life cop shootings happened because it *looked like* the person drew some kind of weapon. so my point: look past the 'funny hair brush act' and see the real message before making a joke about things) This scene is not funny, it's more pugnant because it makes an important point, not a pun

text: As good as this movie looks something just doesn‚Äôt sit right with me. I just don‚Äôt kinda like how this trailer portrays public high schools in lower income neighborhoods. Now Starr‚Äôs experiences were based off Angie Thomas‚Äô(the author) and how she had to live a double life basically. I get that. But I feel as if the movie kinda overgeneralizes about how students at private and public schools function. I‚Äôve known girls who have gotten addicted to meth and one who got a pregnant yet their parents payed 13 grand a year for their education. I know the tuition price because I was gonna attend there as well but stuff fell short. All the while I‚Äôve known dedicated kids who attend public schools,dedicate their life to their education etc etc. But because they go to a C minus Niche rated school they‚Äôre not taken seriously.Where does this narrative leave those dedicated students who DO go to schools in lower income neighborhoods. I hope I‚Äôm wrong. I really do. This is just a trailer so I still have high hopes. Just that wording about the school gave me a weird feeling. But I‚Äôm probably just reading in too deep into it and it‚Äôs gonna be a great movie. In elementary I  went to private but hung around neighborhoods on the lower economic scale. Where food and necessities are just more affordable. Most of my classmates had dads who golfed on the weekend while My dad had to work. So dear god I pray this movie executes it‚Äôs message well.

text: This movie is an unbelievable affront to Law Enforcement Officers everywhere. Though I am retired, we dedicated Our Lives to fighting criminals and protecting the innocent. This movie makes us look like bastards and murderers. It is wrong. It is especially wrong to sensationalize racism, to say it is more than it is, and to say that all police officers are wrong and horrible. There is a United States Supreme Court case, Tennessee versus Gardner, that specifically authorized is officers to utilize lethal Force when it is objectively reasonable. Want to subject is given clear and distinct verbal commands to remain where he is. Once stepped out of the vehicle, and then he goes back to the vehicle, and is told to stop, we believe it is to retrieve a weapon to kill us. That is a reasonable assumption, because many officers have died for exactly that reason. The subject then pulls out an object with his hand. He is again told to stop and refuses. The officer fires. That is the way it is. The subject would be alive if he had obeyed officers commands. This movie is unbelievable and that it ignores all of this. I call on police officers firefighters Medics security guards and all good and decent people to boycott any theater that attempts to play this. Because they are attempting only to destroy law enforcement and Advocate our destruction.

text: The real story, the one in the book, never had Khalil, the boy who was shot,  grab the hairbrush. The only thing he did was check on Starr to asks if she was okay. I have no idea why the movie changed it because people who haven‚Äôt read the book will now interpret it wrong and may say the shooting was justified but that isn‚Äôt what actually happened.  If you read the book you can clearly see that the police officer was being excessive and more aggressive than was necessary. The cop was not doing his job right. The reason everyone was protesting and rioting was because this was a 16 year old black kid living in a neighborhood that was known for drugs, violence, etc, and that was ultimately the reason he was shot, due to racial profiling the cop just assumed they were bad kids and they were up to no good. And let‚Äôs be honest if this were a white person or a person with light skin this would not have been the result, there are steps that need to be taken and there‚Äôs proper protocol for everything. Because he was a black man he was automatically suspected.   And to the people who may say that the cop was scared for his life, that‚Äôs not a reason to take the life of a kid, of a living breathing person, because of an error in judgment. Cops are properly trained for those types of situations, and what the cop did in this story was clearly wrong and misguided.  So no, no it was not his fault that he got shot, he didn‚Äôt point the gun at himself.
author: Gabby T.

text: This story, this book, and this movie were not made to depict the police in a negative way it was made to bring attention to the fact that black people everywhere are subjected to racial profiling even if it‚Äôs not necessarily intentional. The people saying that stories like this only cause a divide and make the problem worse, it only does so when people automatically assume the worst, when people don‚Äôt look at the whole picture.   Stories like this do need to be out there. Not for the sake of demonizing the police, making martyrs out of people, and creating a divide; but for the sake of starting and creating a conversation. If you never speak about the problem it starts to become the normal, and we can‚Äôt let taking the lives of the innocent because of situations like the one in the book become normal. Bringing attention the problem allows for a window of opportunity to make a change.   ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs the point of having a voice if you‚Äôre gonna be silent in the moments you shouldn‚Äôt be?‚Äù

text: My biggest problem with this movie is the fact that Amandla Stenberg had been cast as Starr. It doesn't matter what Angie said, the way she chose to portray Starr on cover of her book is what was expected and that was a dark-skinned black girl. Not only is Amandla light skinned, she's mixed race. The book says that Starr is a cross between her parents and in this movie she's lighter that BOTH OF THEM. After all of Amandla talk about being pro black and quote unquote "dropping out" of Black Panther to let darker skinned girls "have a chance", this is something else she also should have deemed important for a darker girl to have. I'm not only upset with her for snatching the role, but also with the casting directors for putting her in it. For some reason, Hollyweird seems to have the misconception that movies featuring dark skinned people won't sell as much but Black Panther was full dark skins and culture and completely smashed the box office. Coincidence? I think not.  I have a problem with accepting biracial people as black because when we do, they become the face of our community and that becomes a problem. They are then deemed the "acceptable" black people and the rest of us are then misrepresented. Don't even tell me that Amandla is black enough because she isn't, she's really not. This just throws Starr's entire story out the window because it's supposed the represent the darker skinned community and the prejudice against us but at the end of the day, I guess Amandla cares more about  making money than the message. The book doesn't portray all cops as being bad in fact the opposite it shows that most cops are good but there are a selected few that are racist and/or abuse their power.  They changed Khalil into reaching into his car for a dark colored brush when he was told to stay still which is reason to shoot in a cops mind. The whole anger and rioting is that Khalil was unarmed and listened and followed instructions of the cop and was still shot 3x. If you want more and you share that with them and they relent and you chose to stay....THAT'S ON YOU. text: Will be interesting to see what *yet another film* on the Black/white, black/cop, and poor/rich divides in our society does. Being that our society is already severed on multiple faults, I'm not expecting much.  From a narrative standpoint, the movie seems to take offence that the shooting of this kid would be in any way justified; However, while it is a tragic event, it wasn't random violence, and its not just the boys friends, family, and neighborhood that are affected. The cop will have to live with the fact he shot an unarmed man, and the black community will never let him move past it. The entire police-force of that city and, with the advent of social media, most of the nation, will have to deal with the fallout of an outraged congregation.  Multiple episodes in the Cop drama, Blue Bloods,  deal with this facet- Its set in a modern day progressive New-York, and deals with the White, Irish-Catholic family that is the Reagan clan. It does a very good job of showing that even those "in power" are not always the most powerful people in a situation- I'd highly recommend watching it as well as this movie, so that you get to see the issue from both sides- One look from the point of view of a smart, black teenager from the ghetto, and that of her family, the other from a family of honorable cops (most notably Danny and Jamie, one a seasoned, hard-ball detective who steps on the line, the other a lawyer turned cop, your classic boy-scout who follows the rules as far as they're written).   It'll also be interesting to see how many people care that the shooting of this 17 year-old kid, while tragic, is more understandable if viewed from another perspective beyond the one shown in the trailer and, as I can reasonably assume, the movie.  While I will agree that the use of force is something to be avoided *if possible*, the definition of just how possible it is has to stop at some point. A cops first job is to take criminals, whoever they may be, off the street, and the second job entailed in that is to keep ordinary, law abiding people safe. In this particular case, the officer doesn't know what the man he just pulled over has, and it could be something deadly to him or to any nearby citizens- for sake of example, a gun.   All that taken into consideration, you are now in the following scenario: A man you just pulled over is reaching inside his car, to grab some object. It is dark, and you don't know the man, so would have no idea as to whether he is violent or not but for the at most couple of minutes you've known him since pulling him over. As he pulls his hand back, you can see an object in his hand- You don't know what the object is- Maybe its a gun, maybe its a hair-brush. Pair that with the fact the individual in question has not only disobeyed your commands, but is currently in a decently high-stress situation- Being pulled over (for whatever reason). Hes roughly 20 feet from you- A fair distance to have to close with a knife, but possible given the circumstances, and more than within easy range of a handgun- You aren't a far off observer, you are right there, in the thick of it. Your life, the life of his passenger, his life, and anyone nearby hangs in the balance of whether or not you act on what this man pulled out of his car.  What do you do?

text: This trailer worries me - the book has so much inner dialogue and frustration and understanding that a movie I feel can't accurately portray without changing bits and pieces. Obviously, a movie is generally not identical to the book inspiration, but changing too much can be dangerous for the message.  Something that bugged me was Khalil's representation in the situation with the cops in the scene where he gets shot. In the book, Khalil is VERY concerned for Starr's safety so he leans ever so slightly into the car to ask her if she's okay. The cop sees the hairbrush, assumes Khalil is threatening to shoot him and then acts. text: I understand he was shot for not following the officers instructions, and because he was reaching for something inside the car, yes, he had it coming. However the officer could've gone for the thigh, shoulder, elbow, hand, something non-lethal that would incapacitate him. Also the wiki says in the movie the boy was shot three times, that's 2 shots overkill. But 1st: What were they even pulled over for? At 1:05 and 1:08 there were no stop signs, no traffic lights to run, and it didn't seem like they were speeding, so what were they pulled over for? 2nd: Couldn't he have just tased him? Google says police tasers can fire from up to 30 feet, I'm sure he was in range. I agree, the riots and molotovs and such are way overboard and unnecessary, if you're going to protest, do it peacefully like The Civil Rights movement, but in truth they should take the officer to court. With Starr sitting in the passenger seat, a witness to exactly what happened, they might be able to get him punished and hopefully even fired for what he's done. "He was caught in the heat of the moment" someone will probably say, well if you can't think quickly enough to get optimal results out of a situation, perhaps you shouldn't be a police officer, or at least be re-assigned to desk duty. To conclude, there were bad moves on both sides.

text: Honestly, it is probably more of a class issue than a race issue. However, grouping up by class especially in America is harder when grouping people by race is so easy especially when the usual identifiers of class; being the way in which you speak, how you carry yourself (posture and gate), and how you treat your possessions (rubbish in the car vs well maintained (not necessarily the value of the vehicle)), are often especially in the media used to identify the different racial cultures in the states.  Someone who exudes the appearance of class is usually attributed with adjectives like 'respectable', 'responsible', and 'rational'. Such a person has things they don't want to lose, values themselves and others and finally doesn't act on impulse. A policeman addressing an individual like this will be less wary that they will draw a pistol, try and escape or exhibit reckless behavior.  On the other hand, someone who lacks this appearance may have an untidy car, unkempt appearance, communicate in slang/pigeon or as though they missed more than a few days of school, have a peculiar/erratic gate/movement or poor posture will cumulatively add up to exude the appearance of low class. Which invokes the words 'unrespectable', 'unresponsible', and 'irrational'. It would be to these people that a question like "Is that your kid in the car?" is an actual question rather than par for the course, and of whom the policeman will be far more wary of drawing a pistol or weapon on him.  Unfortunately, it seems as though most media (even this film does it), actively portrays black communities as being not well off and also exhibiting some elements of 'low class' behavior. It seems as though unlike some other countries classful behavior has become racial signaling in most black communities where proper vernacular is deemed as being 'white' and something to avoid reinforcing the likelihood that people remain socially immobile and in these sectioned communities.  Even in the most ethnically homogenous societies, low-class people can still be picked up on based on the attributes outlined, sometimes with their very first utterance. The exception is that there is no racial sections of society which feel as though being low class is who they are, while there are people still in such countries content with being low class there is no admiration for such class and many openly strive to raise their class in the hopes that they will obtain social positions matching the class they emulate. Even in such homogenous societies, the perceived lower class are roughed up more by police with more injuries and overnight prison stays.  Most of what I refer to are generalizations that people/communities exhibit/perform and tensions caused. There very well may be exceptions, but the rules explain the data and human behavior.  tl:dr - Wealthy or upper-class black people in America are so in spite of rather than because of the low-class culture oft-identified with by the black communities (generalization). Law enforcement is more wary of low-class people who tend to be viewed by all as having less to lose financially and socially while also tending to be more irrational or violence-prone (generalization).

text: All in all - it makes me SICK we as American's have such a divide this day and age of 2018. we came so far, then we set ourselves back - until we admit that "White's" do have privileges and those of other culture or race do not, it will sadly continue, if you are white shaking your head, go be on the flipside and see for yourself. I have not read the book yet, but watching this trailer made my heart sink because a life was lost period. Why because of his color, sadly because of his color.  White or Black, if it would have had the same outcome, who knows, but we do know here, it was because he was black.  All I know is it happens like this a lot in our world and it shouldn't.  What I have seen here was slow movements by him, and his body language said nothing of the sort of being defiant or defensive or to be feared,  he was leisurely hanging back talking to his girl. His movements were slow and he wasn't even turned to the officer when he pulled the hairbrush up by his head, granted  I want to see the whole movie, but that is what I seen in this trailer.  I heard no warning from the officer to stop, drop it, turn around with your hands in the air, NO WARNING - nothing of the sort just a shot, he acted out of fear, but really fear of what?  I would hope an pray the good officers of this world in certain situations, will use their voice first then act on what they see because they are trained correctly, not just an assumption without assessment and yes they have to think fast and on the defense.  Usually, as an officer I would also think, you would have a heightened sense of "danger" or "fear" from the citizens you pull over, here I see nothing but compliance and just a couple of teens out on a date, nothing to be feared of, not even the mood in the voices or their body language would you assume fear, so why would you assume he is a danger. Obviously, this officer has no sense or 6th sense of being for his job, to access the situation, he just acted without thinking, but really he couldn't have felt fear for his life from them.  And a taser would have sufficed, to deploy any other danger of moving in a defensive manner.  We have lost the main groundings of life, the compassion for other humans, love, respect. I don't care who you are, this happens and it needs to stop, but not by violence, by teaching that every life matters in this world, no matter who you are, because we only get one!!!

text: This isn‚Äôt even a true story!    This entire movie and the book have one aim and that is to seperate America. Black Lives Matter and other organisations try to paint a false picture and get people filled with hate through false stories like this one. Hands up don‚Äôt shoot was a lie.  This is what creates division and keeps from Martin Luther King‚Äôs dream. In every one of his speeches he charged his audience to never respond in hate or violence.  ‚ÄúI have a dream that one day down in Alabama, with its vicious racists, with its governor having his lips dripping with the words of interposition and nullification, that one day right down in Alabama little black boys and black girls will be able to join hands with little white boys and white girls as sisters and brothers.‚Äù   When these stories are written to get people to become activists it doesn‚Äôt prompt ‚Äúlittle black boys and black girls to join hands with little white boys and white girls as sisters and brothers.‚Äù It prompts marches and kids  holding up signs that say f*** white people. text: Sometimes the problem is not even with being racist or profiling but rather the lack of proper training for our police officers. A great example that we could learn from is the UK. They use a firearm as a last resort. Sadly, here in the U.S. it is kind of hard to do so because people can be unpredictable. It is still not an excuse to use your last resort weapon as your, "shoot first ask questions later". It's sad seeing our officers shoot people due to misunderstandings. I do agree with others about just following what the officers says. EVEN if you did not do anything wrong. If you get pulled over, just proceed to identify yourself, simple as that. Yes, you DO NOT have to, but you learn in the movie by not obeying a simple task, you put the officer into thinking that there may be something wrong. They need to be cautious because their lives are also in danger, therefore do not give an officer the wrong idea by not obeying. This is where maybe, a better training could come in handy if maybe the officer seems aggressive. When I got pulled over for speeding, there were no complications what so ever. text: I love how the movie isn't just one-sided... like "oh cops are terrible they're racist" but the movie also tells all sides of the story and what the people are feeling. People may think blacks sell drugs and stuff because they want to.. but it's not that. It's because they have to resort to that, after going through something hard.. like for example khalil lost his mom and had to take care of his younger brother, so he started selling drugs. But it also tells the police officer's side of the story. Like Starr's uncle said, he wouldn't shoot if it was a white man in a suit. He also tells Starr what it's like in the situation. Things go through their mind like "oh, is the girl okay, did she just get raped, is he not following orders because he's hiding something, is he going to reach for a weapon?" One thing I also learned though.. is that if a white man covered in tattoos, piercings, wearing pants that sag and a tanktop, and he was disobeying orders... There's a 50% chance the cop would shoot and not say "put your hands up" compared to if the guy was wearing a suit, well dressed, and had a nice car. This movie gives a good message overall, and explains what goes through somebody's mind when they see this happen. I already saw the movie, but I'd honestly go see the movie 10 more times.

text: For anyone watching the trailer and thinking that reaching for the brush made no sense let me explain it with a very minor spoiler. He was casually talking to Starr telling her to calm down because he got pulled over for no reason and as he was casually talking he reached for the brush to brush his hair as he waited for the cop to come back to his car. (I dont remember for sure but I think he caught a glance of himself in the sideview mirror and wanted to adjust his hair because he is into his image). He wasn't thinking and did not realize how his actions could be interpreted. But he never pointed the brush at the cop or even lifted the brush up, as soon as he leaned out of the car the cop was already pointing the gun at him. It all happens very fast in the movie and comes out of nowhere. He should have not reached into the car and listend to Starr but the cop was also new and nervous and in the moment of confusion shot out of panic. The trailer slows down the scene to let it register with the audience that he gets shot over nothing. This movie doesn't blame cops, it blames reckless/panicked cops and corrupt cops. Both sides of the argument are explored in this movie. They explore the life of a black american trapped in the ghetto and just trying to get by, the actual criminals and druglords manipulating youngs to do their work so the young can have money to escape the ghetto, and the complicated job of a cop who has to assume the worst in a bad neighboorhood. And ofcourse the cops who are corrupt and immoral and racially profile and the shooter who is just unfit for the job and panics under that sort of circumstance.

text: I really want to watch this movie üò©‚ù§Ô∏è

Just finished the book and plan to see this movie soon but I have several serious questions and concerns about not only this story but actual real life society too: Why do some people just not do what law enforcement officers tell them to do? If you actually listened to what you are told to do you could avoid what could escalate into a dangerous situation. What has happened to respect for authority and all human beings in general? Why do people justify crime as the only necessary means to come up with income or respect? Why do people think they have territorial rights to geographical areas that they don‚Äôt own? Why don‚Äôt people apply discipline and seek to educate themselves to better their lives? Why is it so difficult to speak proper English? Why are children and adults carrying weapons intended to intimidate, rob and kill with? The only thing standing between us and a completely lawless world are the men and women who risk their own lives every day to serve and protect, those individuals have been killed in the line of duty by criminals day in and day out and with the firearms that blight this country being used against them in crimes so is it any wonder innocent people are killed when they don‚Äôt comply with straightforward commands? LISTEN and live. Playing the victim because of your race is inexcusable. Find a way to educate yourself, take responsibility for your actions and choices, distance yourself from criminals and crime. When a civilian is killed there are groups of people who use that situation to riot and loot. How is destroying property and stealing from innocent people who had nothing to do with the situation justified? This story does nothing but blame, accuse and fan the flames of HATE.

text: People keeps commenting stuffs about race, propaganda, cops brutality when we completely forgot about the fact that starr and khalil is just a teenager. A teenager who could have a much brighter future, free of violence and injustice in the society. A teenager who could create a change to their community but people waisted their opportunity to do so because their mindset is imprinted by hate. I think the words "THUGLIFE" sets off a really powerful message that is so relevant to what we are dealing right now because we are so caught up with fighting off something thats completely irrelevant to fight for.   we emphasizes race to the society as if each of them should be mattered no matter what consequences should be taken, but how about us? The youth? The agent of change? Talking about not all white are good and not all black are bad? It doesnt make any sense. At the end of the day, what defines your wellbeing is what you do, not by a statement that you address. Doesn't matter what you look like  But whats concerning in issues like this is how the cycle keeps going and how it affects the younger generations to keep on following the social constructs thats imprinted on hate. Hate creates everything from violence to propaganda or supremacy. Because when we hate, we disagree on things. Seeing people who fight over about conversion propaganda, cop brutality, gun violence just wont solve the fact that if we keep hating on one side, theres always gonna be hostility and no justice.  People keep forgetting that theyre just kids, figuring out life and learning from it. But they had to be exposes in a world full of hate at a young age that it creates fear from both side which can never be compromised if we keep talking about culture and race. Yes you can be differentiated on the color of your skin or the culture you are from, but no matter what makes you, YOU, we can all agree that we are once a teenager trying to figure out life and fighting off of the fear of hate that creates injustice to our life.

text: It honestly makes me sad that people are still not understanding the message of the movie. The movie or book is not just propaganda, it is set to inform society that our stereotypes can be deadly. Implicit Bias exist for a reason. Prejudice does not always have to be intentional but it does not mean it is less offensive or impactful. When people see a young black man at night with a hood in the hood they automatically characterize him as a criminal. No one has the given right to take someone‚Äôs life. If a suspect IS armed it takes one shot to the LEG or LEGS to sedate not 3 or more in the chest to kill. There are so many stories of decades and decades of racial injustice that needs to be heard. The movie is an outlet for those stories to be reached. If you do not understand I suggest research to get educated.   ..And that is my Ted Talk

text: When I went to go see this movie, I went alone because I knew that I would cry....which is exactly happened.  Except I didn‚Äôt just cry, I was SOBBING.  This movie really hit me hard because it made me think of the kids at my old high school v. My actual friends.   98% of my classmates were white.  Most of them rich, preppy, from well-to-do families, and simply SHELTERED and IGNORANT.  Almost none of them saw how lucky they were to live in such an affluent area with essentially nothing to truly worry about.  They never saw or were able to comprehend that not everyone has the same privileges and advantages as them; they believed all of the negative stereotypes that the media exaggerates so heavily.  Their ignorance, naivety, and close-mindedness astounded me. To be completely honest, I‚Äôm an 18 year old white girl; I know that that shouldn‚Äôt matter but unfortunately in this fucked-up world it does.  A lot of people are saying that this movie really hit home to them because they are black, Muslim, etc, and have gone through the same hardships.  I can‚Äôt say that I have had the same experiences as them, and I will never EVER say that I truly understand what it‚Äôs like because I don‚Äôt.  But just because something doesn‚Äôt apply to you, doesn‚Äôt mean that it‚Äôs nonexistent to others

text: This movie is so amazing and so powerful. It has one of the best messages a movie can have about hate, and the scene that displays that message the best is without a doubt the scene with Sekani. Hell, when my class watched it, everyone SCREAMED at that part. We usually don't react that much to movies, except at the funny moments. That's how powerful this movie can be. I think everyone should watch it. Another great thing about this movie is the lead. I usually don't care about the main character of movies like this, but I really liked Starr. She never felt like an actor; she felt like a real person that I knew, and that's really good acting right there. And she has the best and most charming and most genuine smile in the world that just makes you want to smile too. The father's pretty good as well. He inspires his kids to do what they think is right and to never be quiet. That's just an awesome parent right there. And the mom's pretty realistic. I mean, she supports Starr for doing the right thing, but she also wants to protect her. The scene where she yells at Starr for going to a protest is so relatable and I think that's exactly what my own mother would say to me if I did what Starr did. Overall this is an awesome movie and everyone should see it.
